# Social media app features brainstorm

Thu, 16 Jul 26

### Product Vision

- Real-life-first social network: all connections require physical, face-to-face presence
  - Antithesis of follower-farming: no one can grow a network without actually meeting people
  - Tagline direction: “the social media where you actually have to be social”
  - App name TBD; strong preference for a verb-form name (like “Google it” or “tap in”)
    - Working title: “Tap In”
    - Prior art to check: Friendster (taken); name will emerge organically like Instagram’s did
- Core thesis: digital social graphs should mirror real-world relationship density
  - Instagram’s original identity (retro filters) drifted far from its current form; this app’s identity should be structurally enforced, not just cultural

---

### Social Graph Mechanics

- Single relationship type: “friends” only
  - No followers, no following, no asymmetric relationships
  - One number on your profile: total friend count
  - Mutual by definition: if A is friends with B, B is friends with A
- Influencer model is fundamentally redefined
  - Status comes from the size of your real-world network
  - You cannot buy reach; you have to physically meet people
- Friend count as social signal
  - High friend count = genuinely well-connected person in real life
  - No vanity metric inflation possible through follow-backs or purchased followers

---

### Connection Protocol

- Primary mechanism: NFC tap
  - Both users open the app, tap phones together, connection is established
  - Rationale for NFC as primary:
    - Near-universal hardware support across modern smartphones
    - Requires genuine physical proximity (cannot be done remotely)
    - Frictionless UX: no scanning, no typing, no searching
  - Alternatives considered and deprioritized:
    - QR code scanning: viable fallback, slightly more friction
    - Bluetooth: possible but less precise proximity signal
    - Decision: NFC is the best current option; revisit if superior technology emerges
- Connection is instantaneous and bilateral
  - No “request and accept” flow: tap = connected
  - Both users see the new friend appear in their list immediately

---

### Privacy Model and Profile Visibility

- All profiles are private by default, with no opt-out to public
  - A profile is only visible to confirmed mutual friends
  - Non-friends see nothing: no posts, no bio, no friend count
  - This is not a “privacy setting”; it is the architecture of the platform
- Comparison to Instagram private profiles:
  - Instagram private = you choose to restrict; public is the default
  - This app: private is the only mode; there is no public mode
  - Implication: no lurking, no discovery through browsing, no algorithmic surfacing of strangers
- Discovery is entirely IRL
  - You cannot find someone by searching their name
  - The only path to connection is physical presence and NFC tap

---

### Unfriend Flow and Notification Design

- Unfriending is unilateral: one person removes the other, connection is severed for both
  - The removed person loses the friend from their list automatically
- Notification on unfriend: confirmed feature, but wording is an open design question
  - Option A (named): “Scotty unfriended you”
    - Transparent but high potential for conflict, especially among younger users
  - Option B (anonymous): “You lost a friend”
    - Softer; user must check their own list to identify who it was
    - Preferred direction in discussion
  - Open question: at high friend counts (40+), anonymous notification is effectively undetectable
    - Most people actively track ~15 close contacts; beyond that, churn goes unnoticed
  - Recommendation: A/B test both variants; monitor downstream behavior (blocks, reports, churn)
  - Risk flag: named unfriend notifications could generate conflict, especially in teen/high school demographics

