### Opt-In City-Level Co-Location Notifications

- Feature: when two mutual friends are in the same city at the same time, both receive a nudge
  - “Maz is in Toronto. You should tap in.”
  - Requires both users to have location sharing opted in
- Granularity: city-level only, not neighborhood or street-level
  - Protects privacy: you know someone is in your city, not their exact location
  - Reduces stalking/safety risk vs. precise location sharing
- Opt-in architecture:
  - Both users must independently opt in for the nudge to trigger
  - If either user has location off, no notification is sent to either party
- Real-world use case that motivated this feature:
  - Two childhood friends both spent New Year’s in Paris simultaneously
  - Neither knew the other was there; discovered it a week later on a phone call
  - One friend was not on Instagram and missed the posts; this app would have caught it
- Business and professional use case:
  - Met someone at a conference, exchanged taps, forgot about them
  - Six months later, both at the same city for different reasons
  - App surfaces the overlap: “You should reconnect”
- Open question: should the nudge include a suggested venue or activity, or just the alert?

