### Event, Concert, and Venue/White-Label Scenarios

- Concert use case (The Weeknd example):
  - Artist has a verified fan base in the app (Spotify-linked or self-declared)
  - At the venue, fans tap in with each other, building a concert-specific sub-network
  - Merch table: tap in to receive 10–20% discount as a verified fan
  - Artist team gets conversion data: how many app users attended, how many bought merch
  - Pay-tier model for artists: guaranteed reach to X verified fans in exchange for platform fee
- NFC wristband integration at events:
  - Precedent: The Weeknd’s ACC Toronto concert (sold out, ~20,000 attendees) used NFC/LED wristbands
    - Wristbands lit up in coordinated colors during the show, visible across the arena
    - Controlled via backend timing system; costly to implement at scale
  - Opportunity: if a venue already issues NFC wristbands (e.g. for access control or experience), white-label the tap-in functionality into that wristband
  - Users tap wristbands together instead of phones; same connection mechanic, different hardware
- Activate venue white-label scenario:
  - Activate is a dark, dimly-lit entertainment venue with multiple activity rooms (hoops, grid, etc.)
  - Already issues NFC wristbands to guests for score tracking on in-venue screens
  - Problem: guests arrive with their own group but have no way to meet other regulars with compatible schedules
  - White-label opportunity:
    - Activate’s existing NFC wristband doubles as a tap-in device
    - Guests can connect with other Activate regulars they meet in-venue
    - Post-visit: find other regulars who want to go back, coordinate group visits
  - Functionality is already partially built into Activate’s hardware; integration is a partnership play
  - Open question: revenue share model with Activate vs. licensing fee vs. co-marketing

